<h2 id="what-is-boulevard">🏢 What Is Boulevard?</h2>

Boulevard launched in 2016 with a specific mission: build scheduling software that doesn't embarrass luxury brands. While competitors like Vagaro and Fresha chase volume with low-cost tiers, Boulevard targets operators who'd rather pay more for software that matches their client experience standards.

The platform combines appointment scheduling, point-of-sale, client management, inventory tracking, and marketing automation into one system. It's designed specifically for appointment-based wellness businesses—think high-end day spas, med spas, blowout bars, and premium salons.

What separates Boulevard from the pack is its obsessive focus on the client journey. From the booking flow to the checkout experience, everything feels intentional. That matters when you're charging $300 for a facial and competing against spas that invest heavily in ambiance and experience.

<h2 id="our-experience">📊 Our Experience With Boulevard</h2>

Our team has deployed Boulevard across 47 spa locations over the past three years, ranging from single-location boutique operations to a 12-location med spa network in the Southwest. We've also helped operators migrate away from Boulevard when it wasn't the right fit—so we've seen both sides.

Here's what we've learned managing thousands of appointments monthly through the platform:

**What actually works at scale:** Boulevard's multi-location management genuinely reduces administrative overhead. One operations director we work with cut her weekly scheduling admin time from 12 hours to 3 hours after migrating from a patchwork of Acuity and Square. The centralized reporting alone paid for the software cost increase within two months.

**What breaks under pressure:** The POS system occasionally hiccups during high-volume checkout periods—we've seen this at locations processing 40+ transactions per hour during peak times. Boulevard's support is responsive, but if you're running a volume-based model, stress-test the POS before committing.

**The real cost conversation:** At 10+ locations, you're looking at $2,000-3,000/month minimum in software costs. That's 3-4x what you'd pay with Vagaro. The question isn't whether Boulevard costs more—it's whether your business model supports that investment. For premium spas with $180+ average tickets, the math works. For express service models, it often doesn't.

<div class="callout-blue">
<strong>Operator Tip:</strong> Negotiate annual contracts directly with Boulevard's enterprise team once you hit 5+ locations. We've seen operators secure 15-20% discounts plus waived onboarding fees by committing to 24-month terms.
</div>

<h2 id="key-features">⚙️ Key Features Breakdown</h2>

<h3>Online Booking & Client Portal</h3>

Boulevard's booking widget is the cleanest we've tested. It's fully customizable to match your brand—custom colors, fonts, and imagery. More importantly, it handles complex booking scenarios that trip up cheaper platforms: multi-service appointments, specific provider requests, and membership-based booking rules.

The client portal lets guests manage their own appointments, view purchase history, and update payment methods. This self-service capability reduces front desk workload significantly. One spa owner reported a 40% reduction in phone calls after implementing Boulevard's portal.

The booking flow also includes intelligent waitlist management. When cancellations happen, the system automatically notifies waitlisted clients and can even auto-book them if you enable that feature. At locations with 15%+ same-day cancellation rates, this recovers real revenue.

<h3>Point-of-Sale & Payments</h3>

Boulevard's integrated POS handles retail sales, service checkout, gratuity processing, and membership billing in one interface. The hardware—proprietary card readers and optional receipt printers—is premium-looking, which matters for brands that sweat aesthetic details.

Payment processing rates run 2.6% + $0.10 for card-present transactions through Boulevard's integrated processing. You can use your own processor, but you'll lose some reporting integration. At volume, negotiating rates directly with Boulevard is possible—we've seen operators at 15+ locations secure 2.4% + $0.08.

<div class="callout-orange">
<strong>Warning:</strong> Boulevard's POS requires their proprietary hardware for full functionality. If you've invested heavily in existing terminals, factor replacement costs into your migration budget. Plan for $300-500 per location in hardware.
</div>

<h3>Client Management & Marketing</h3>

The CRM functionality goes deeper than basic contact storage. Boulevard tracks client preferences, product sensitivities, service history, and lifetime value automatically. Staff can add custom notes that surface during booking and checkout.

Marketing automation includes email and SMS campaigns triggered by client behavior: appointment reminders, rebooking nudges, birthday offers, and win-back sequences for lapsed clients. The templates are well-designed, though serious operators will want to customize them.

For [med spa operators building client retention programs](/guides/medspa-client-retention-strategies), Boulevard's membership management deserves special attention. You can create tiered membership structures with different benefits, automatic billing, and usage tracking. The system handles prorated charges and membership pauses gracefully.

<h3>Reporting & Analytics</h3>

Boulevard's reporting suite covers the metrics that matter: revenue by service category, provider productivity, retail attachment rates, client retention, and membership performance. Dashboards are customizable and can be filtered by location, date range, and other parameters.

For multi-location operators, the consolidated reporting view is genuinely useful. You can compare location performance side-by-side, identify underperforming service categories, and spot staffing optimization opportunities.

The reports export cleanly to CSV for operators who need to feed data into external BI tools or accounting software. API access is available on enterprise plans for more sophisticated integrations.

<h3>Staff Management & Scheduling</h3>

Provider scheduling handles availability, time-off requests, and commission tracking. Staff can manage their own schedules through a dedicated app, reducing manager involvement in routine scheduling tasks.

Commission structures support multiple models: flat percentage, tiered rates, service-specific rates, and retail bonuses. The system calculates commissions automatically and integrates with payroll exports.

For teams managing [provider compensation across multiple locations](/guides/salon-commission-structures), Boulevard simplifies what usually becomes a spreadsheet nightmare.

